        <h2 class='stockHeadline'>Introduction to Investing</h2>
        <div class='definition'>
            <p>Definition:</p>
            <p>Investing involves allocating money or resources with the expectation of generating income or profit. 
               The goal of investing is to put your money to work in one or more types of investment vehicles to 
               achieve your financial goals. The primary asset classes include stocks, bonds, real estate, and 
               cash equivalents.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='understandingStocks'>
            <h2>Why Invest?</h2>
            <p>Investing is essential for building wealth over time. Here are some key reasons to invest:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Grow Your Wealth:</strong> Investments have the potential to grow your money faster than a regular savings account.</li>
                <li><strong>Beat Inflation:</strong> Investing helps to combat inflation, which reduces the purchasing power of your money over time.</li>
                <li><strong>Achieve Financial Goals:</strong> Investing can help you achieve long-term financial goals like retirement, buying a house, or funding education.</li>
            </ul>
            <h2>Types of Investments</h2>
            <p>There are various types of investments to consider, each with its own risk and return profile:</p>
            <ol id='list'>
                <li>Stocks:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Represent ownership in a company and a claim on part of the company's profits.</li>
                    <li>Stocks can offer high returns but come with higher risk.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Bonds:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Debt instruments issued by corporations or governments to raise capital.</li>
                    <li>Provide fixed interest payments over a specified period.</li>
                    <li>Considered lower risk compared to stocks.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Mutual Funds:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Pools of money from many investors to invest in a diversified portfolio of stocks, bonds, or other assets.</li>
                    <li>Managed by professional fund managers.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>ETFs (Exchange-Traded Funds):</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Similar to mutual funds but trade on stock exchanges like individual stocks.</li>
                    <li>Offer diversification and can be bought and sold throughout the trading day.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Real Estate:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Investing in property or real estate investment trusts (REITs).</li>
                    <li>Provides rental income and potential for property value appreciation.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Commodities:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Investing in physical goods like gold, silver, oil, and agricultural products.</li>
                    <li>Can hedge against inflation and market volatility.</li>
                </ul>
            </ol>
        </div>
